TestNG Setup & Best Practices (March 5th)
1. TestNG Plugin Installation
Process: Go to Help → Eclipse Marketplace → search for "TestNG for Eclipse" and install.

Tip: Select all, accept the terms (select "Trust" if prompted), and proceed with the installation.

2. Adding Dependencies
You need to add the TestNG dependency to your pom.xml file.

The group ID is usually org.testng.

3. Creating TestNG Classes
While creating a package, you can directly create a TestNG class.

Execution Order: By default, TestNG methods execute based on the alphabetical order of the method names.

Priority: To control the execution sequence, use the priority attribute: @Test(priority = 1).

Reporting: TestNG automatically generates a test report after execution.

Refining Code Structure & Annotations
Handling Drivers: If you initialize the driver inside every test method, the tests will create and run in multiple different browser instances, which is inefficient.

Avoiding Redundancy: To avoid duplicate lines of code for creating the driver, use the @BeforeClass annotation.

Method Example: public void setupBrowser() { ... } — place your driver initialization logic here.

Cleanup: Use the @AfterClass annotation for methods that should run after all test methods in the class have finished (e.g., driver.quit()).

Individual Setup: Use @BeforeMethod for code that needs to run before every individual test method.
